,"Coeliac disease","Chronic infection with Clonorchis sinensis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChronic infection with \u003Cstrong\u003EClonorchis sinensis\u003C/strong\u003E (Chinese liver fluke) is a significant risk factor for cholangiocarcinoma. Clonorchis is endemic in parts of Southeast Asia, particularly China, Vietnam and Korea. It is transmitted through the consumption of raw, freshwater fish. The parasite causes chronic inflammation and injury to the biliary epithelium, leading to increased cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute viral infection that does not cause chronic liver disease or increase cancer risk. \u003Cstrong\u003EPeutz-Jeghers syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with an increased risk of gastrointestinal cancers, but nor cholangiocarcinoma. \u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects digestion and nutrient absorption. \u003Cstrong\u003ECoeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune condition affecting the small intestine and is not associated with biliary tract cancers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important risk factors for biliary tract cancers include primary sclerosing cholangitis, choledochal cysts, hepatolithiasis, and chronic inflammation from parasitic infections like Opisthorchis viverrini.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic inflammation from parasitic infections, particularly Clonorchis sinensis and Opisthorchis viverrini, increases risk of cholangiocarcinoma","Other major risk factors for biliary tract cancers include primary sclerosing cholangitis, choledochal cysts, and gallstones"],"references":["Arnold M, Abnet CC, Neale RE, Vignat J, Giovannucci EL, McGlynn KA, Bray F. Global Burden of 5 Major Types of Gastrointestinal Cancer. Gastroenterology. 2020 Jul;159(1):335-349.e15. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2020.02.068. Epub 2020 Apr 2. PMID: 